Research Question¶

Do economic conditions including changes to employment rates and household income impact the chances of divorce in the United States?

Background & Prior Work¶

Divorce rates and the divorce culture in the United States has been a prominent topic that is being discussed both among the people and the academia to this day. People generally tend to state how finance is often a reason for divorce among the couples. We decided to test this statement through data analysis and compare divorce rates to the unemployment rate and the household income.

While conducting background research on the topic we found many interesting facts. First, we found that multiple articles state that with the improvement in the economy the divorce rates go up. According to a CNBC article titled “Your marriage could suffer due to the strong economy”, there is indeed a correlation between the state of the economy and divorce rates. In periods of economic growth, it seems that the rate of divorces also grows as well. The reasoning behind this correlation is that “when forced to weigh damaged marriages against tight budgets and uncertain financial outlooks, many spouses seem more willing to try and wait it out” (CNBC). This statement by CNBC also seems to be supported by TheAtlantic.

Additionally, we found that a third of the couples who live together are not married because of financial concerns. On the other hand, the married couples stated that finance was barely even an important factor in their marriage decision (PewResearch). Hence this data does suggest that some potential hesitancy of marriage is due to finance, but it does not quite prove it. An article by MarketWatch claims that their studies “...found that 41% of divorced Gen Xers and 29% of Boomers say they ended their marriage due to disagreements about money” (MarketWatch). Therefore, although most articles do tend to show how an improved economy causes the divorce rate to go up, some research findings seem to disagree with that. This fits more with our common knowledge of finance being the one of the primary reasons for divorce among the couples. Our project is meant to help and find out the correlation between the household income, unemployment rate, and the divorce rate, to hopefully come closer to the right answer.

References (include links):

  • 1) https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/31/your-marriage-could-suffer-due-to-the-strong-economy.html
  • 2) https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2014/02/why-more-divorces-are-a-good-sign-for-the-economy/283890/
  • 3) https://www.pewresearch.org/social-trends/2019/11/06/marriage-and-cohabitatio-in-the-u-s/
  • 4) https://www.marketwatch.com/story/this-common-behavior-is-the-no-1-predictor-of-whether-youll-get-divorced-2018-01-10

Hypothesis¶

Our team hypothesizes that economic downturns exacerbate the stress that couples experience. The increased stress of job security and of pay cuts likely increases the financial pressures of marriage. This increased pressure increases marital problems leading to higher divorce rates during economic downturns. We believe that increase in unemployment rates and decrease in household income associated with the health of the economy will correlate to higher divorce rates in America.

Dataset(s)¶

  • Dataset Name: MS-1. Marital Status of the Population 15 Years Old and Over by Sex, Race and Hispanic Origin: 1950 to Present
  • Link to the dataset: https://www.census.gov/data/tables/time-series/demo/families/marital.html
  • Number of observations: 34
  • This dataset gives the number of married and divorced people as collected by the government census from 1950 to 2021, which we will use to get the rate of divorce.
  • Dataset Name: Table H-9. Type of Household--All Households by Median and Mean Income: 1980 to 2020
  • Link to the dataset: https://www.census.gov/data/tables/time-series/demo/income-poverty/historical-income-households.html
  • Number of observations: 42
  • This dataset gives the median and mean incomes of all households as collected by the government census from 1980 to 2020, of which we will use the median income.
  • Dataset Name: Labor Force Statistics from the Current Population Survey
  • Link to the dataset: https://data.bls.gov/timeseries/LNS14000000?years_option=all_years
  • Number of observations: 74
  • This dataset gives the unemployment rate over the years 1948-2022.
  • Dataset Name: Household Debt Service Payments as a Percent of Disposable Personal Income
  • Link to the dataset: https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/TDSP
  • Number of observations: 41
  • This helps us understand the real costs of mortages, and how it changes over time from 1980 to 2021.

Although the number of observations for each dataset seems a bit low, these observations are all for values gathered over an entire year. We need these yearly observations in order to get a good look at how our relationships change over time. We chose these datasets because we want to see how the changes in the household income and unemployment rate affect the divorce rates throughout a wide set of years. We will combine them by looking at the correlation between divorce rate and household income and the correlation between divorce rate and unemployment rate.

# Convert a string to integer and remove any commas
# ex) 12,345 -> 12345
def convert_int(str_in):
    str_in = str_in.strip()
    try:
        str_in = str_in.replace(',', '')
        output = int(str_in)
    except:
        output = np.nan
    return output
In [7]:
# Remove weird symbols from the year column of the divorce rate dataset
def remove_stuff(str_in):
    try:
        str_in = str_in.replace('..', '')
        if 'r' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('r', '')
        if 's' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('s', '')
        if '*' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('*', '')
        output = str_in
    except:
        output = np.nan
    return output

# Cleaned code for divorce rates
df_divorce = pd.read_csv('Divorce_Rate - Sheet1.csv');

# Remove first two rows which are full of garbage values and reset the index
df_divorce = df_divorce.iloc[2:]
df_divorce = df_divorce.reset_index(drop=True)

# Convert the number married and number divorced to int
# men data
df_divorce['Married'] = df_divorce['Married'].apply(convert_int)
df_divorce['Divorced'] = df_divorce['Divorced'].apply(convert_int)

# women data
df_divorce['Married.1'] = df_divorce['Married.1'].apply(convert_int)
df_divorce['Divorced.1'] = df_divorce['Divorced.1'].apply(convert_int)

# Combine the data for men and the data for women to get a total over both sexes
df_divorce['Total Married'] = df_divorce['Married'] + df_divorce['Married.1']
df_divorce['Total Divorced'] = df_divorce['Divorced'] + df_divorce['Divorced.1']

# We are only using the year, total married, and total divorced columns
df_divorce = df_divorce.filter(['Year', 'Total Married', 'Total Divorced'], axis=1)

# Create a new column that represents the proportion of divorced couples compared to married columns
df_divorce['Divorce/Married'] = df_divorce['Total Divorced'] / df_divorce['Total Married']

# Clean up the year column by removing weird periods and letters and *
df_divorce['Year'] = df_divorce['Year'].apply(remove_stuff)

# Reverse dataframe to go from earliest to latest years
df_divorce = df_divorce[::-1]
df_divorce = df_divorce.reset_index(drop=True)
#df_divorce = df_divorce.drop_duplicates()

clean2011 = df_divorce[df_divorce['Year'] == '2011']
clean2011A = clean2011['Divorce/Married'].mean()
clean2011B = clean2011['Total Divorced'].mean()
clean2011C = clean2011['Total Married'].mean()

df_divorce = df_divorce.drop_duplicates(subset=['Year'])

i = df_divorce[df_divorce['Divorce/Married'] == '2011'].index
df_divorce.loc[i, 'Divorce/Married'] = clean2011A
i = df_divorce[df_divorce['Total Divorced'] == '2011'].index
df_divorce.loc[i, 'Total Divorced'] = clean2011B
i = df_divorce[df_divorce['Total Married'] == '2011'].index
df_divorce.loc[i, 'Total Married'] = clean2011C

# Function used to clean up the years column in the household income dataset
# It is very much brute force because all the numbers in the parenthesis are different
def remove_parens(str_in):
    str_in = str_in.strip()
    try:
        str_in = str_in.replace('(', '')
        str_in = str_in.replace(')', '')
        if '40' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('40', '')
        if '39' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('39', '')
        if '38' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('38', '')
        if '37' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('37', '')
        if '36' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('36', '')
        if '35' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('35', '')
        if '30' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('30', '')
        if '29' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('29', '')
        if '25' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('25', '')
        if '24' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('24', '')
        if '23' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('23', '')
        if '22' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('22', '')
            
        # different format for these so I don't break the 20__ and 19__ years
        if '1987 21' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('1987 21', '1987')
        if '1985 20' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('1985 20', '1985')
        if '1984 19' in str_in:
            str_in = str_in.replace('1984 19', '1984')
        output = str_in
        output = output.strip()
    except:
        output = np.nan
    return output

# Cleaning data for household income
df_income = pd.read_csv('h09ar.csv');

# Rename columns to get the correct column names for each column
df_income = df_income.rename(columns={'All Households': 'Year', 'Unnamed: 1': 'Number (thousands)',
                          'Unnamed: 2': 'Median (current dollars)', 'Unnamed: 3': 'Median (2020 dollars)',
                         'Unnamed: 4': 'Mean (current dollars)', 'Unnamed: 5': 'Mean (2020 dollars)'})

# Remove the top two rows because they are garbage values and reset index
df_income = df_income.iloc[2:]
df_income = df_income.reset_index(drop=True)

# We will use only the year and median household income
# We chose to use median income instead of mean because it is more representative
# of the general populace
df_income = df_income.filter(['Year', 'Median (2020 dollars)'])
df_income = df_income.rename(columns={'Median (2020 dollars)': 'median'}) # easier name to use

# Used previously defined functions to remove the weird parenthesis numbers in the year column
# And to convert the median value to int
df_income['Year'] = df_income['Year'].apply(remove_parens)
df_income['median'] = df_income['median'].apply(convert_int)

# There are duplicate rows for years 2013 and 2017, so
# we decided to average the two medians together for each.
mean2013 = df_income[df_income['Year'] == '2013']
mean2013 = mean2013['median'].mean()
mean2017 = df_income[df_income['Year'] == '2017']
mean2017 = mean2017['median'].mean()

# Drop the duplicate row for 2013 and 2017
df_income = df_income.drop_duplicates(subset=['Year'])

# Update the median value in the table to the average
i = df_income[df_income['Year'] == '2013'].index
df_income.loc[i, 'median'] = mean2013
i = df_income[df_income['Year'] == '2017'].index
df_income.loc[i, 'median'] = mean2017

# Reverse dataframe so earlier years come first and reset index to fix indices
df_income = df_income[::-1]
df_income = df_income.reset_index(drop=True)
df_income

#Load the data
df_householddebt = pd.read_csv('household-debt-data.csv')

# rename columns 
df_householddebt.columns = ['Year', 'TDSP'] 

#Keep only year value
df_householddebt['Year'] = df_householddebt['Year'].str[:4]

#create a new dataframe that averages out the TDSP per year
quarters_averaged = df_householddebt.groupby('Year').transform('mean')

#When the mean now applied for rows by year, lets drop the extra year rows in both frames
quarters_averaged = quarters_averaged.drop_duplicates()
df_householddebt_yearly = df_householddebt.drop_duplicates(subset = ['Year'])

#to get them ready to merge, lets reset both their indexes
quarters_averaged = quarters_averaged.reset_index()
df_householddebt_yearly = df_householddebt_yearly.reset_index()

#now, we replace the TDSP values with the averaged ones from our other frame
df_householddebt_yearly['TDSP'] = quarters_averaged['TDSP'] 
df_householddebt_yearly = df_householddebt_yearly[['Year', 'TDSP']].copy()

Household Debt¶

Household Debt is calculated as TDSP, which is the ratio of total required household debt payments to total disposable income. This calculation takes quarterly mortgage payments and divides by total quarterly disposable personal income. This helps us understand the real costs of mortages, and how it changes over time.¶

Regression Analysis¶

We will use linear regression to check if there is a relationship between each of our variables and the divorce rate. Our null hypothesis is that there is no relationship between the variable and divorce rate and our alternate hypothesis is that there is a relationship between the variable and divorce rate. If we can get a p-value that is small (less than 0.05), then we can reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is a significant correlation between the variable and divorce rate.

Household Income¶

First, we want to plot a regression line graph to see if the relationship between median household income and divorce rate is approximately linear. This tells us if we can use linear regression or not.

Result¶

Null hypothesis = no correlation between TDSP and DM up until 2021

Alternate hypothesos = TDSP and DM are correlated up until 2021

What is clear is that this is a very poor model, here is why:

  • low R squared value shows our regression line is poor
  • T value is bigger for our intercept than for TDSP, further evidence our regression is poor
  • F stat is small and the difference between adjusted F stat and F stat is not particuarly big
  • residuals are not normally distributed

Result: No strong correlation. P is greater than alpha. Accept the null hypothesis. Only 14% of the variance in Divorce/Married corresponds to variance in TDSP.

Discussion¶

The model created above clearly does not do a good job at modeling the relationship between the two variables, and this can be attributed to the way TDSP decreased after 2008. After 2009, the economy was relanaced and the measure of household debt decreased. What this points to is that economic turmoils can cause radically changes that literally 'break' certain variables. Because TDSP is calcualted as the total required household debt payments to total disposable income, rebalancing after the recession either caused total disposable income to increase dramatically, or household debt payments changed radically. Given the 2009 recession's ties to subprime mortrages, it is likely that the household debt payments changed substantially.

For this reason, it may be intersting to understand how TDSP and Divorce/Married were correlated before this economic turmoil dramatically changed TDSP. Below, I remove the rows after 2009, and do a second regression on the data before 2009.

Result up until 2009¶

This second regression on the data up till 2008 shows we have a much better model and the two variables are correlated.

Null hypothesis = no correlation up until 2008

Alternate hypothesis = they are correlated up to 2008

This is a better model, here is why:

  • R squared value is very high and is close adjusted R squared, showing our model is a good fit
  • The residuals are more evenly spread.
  • P values are similar for both, showing both variables are significant to the regression, evidence of good fit

  • F-Prob is very small, and F-Statistic is very large, showing more evidence of a linear relationship

  • Despite this, it must be pointed out that this has a considerably smaller sample size.

Result: Strong correlation. P is smaller than alpha so we reject the null hypothesis. 87.3% of the variance in Divorce/Married corresponds to variance in TDSP.

Discussion¶

Overall, it seems that TDSP and Divorce/Married were strongly correlated before the 2009 recession, indicated by our second model. During the rebalancing period after the 2009 recession, it seems that changes were made to mortages, and TDSP no longer correlates, as indicated by our first model.
